# User Management Lab (Windows & Linux)

## Objective
Practice creating a user, granting administrator privileges, verifying the account, and deleting the user in both Windows and Linux systems.

---

# Windows (PowerShell)

## Create User
New-LocalUser -Name "testuser" -Password (Read-Host -AsSecureString)

## View Existing Users
Get-LocalUser

## Add User to Administrators Group
Add-LocalGroupMember -Group "Administrators" -Member "testuser"

## Verify Group Members
Get-LocalGroupMember -Group "Administrators"

## Run Command Prompt as the User
runas /user:testuser cmd

## Delete User
Remove-LocalUser -Name "testuser"

## Verify Deletion
Get-LocalUser

---

# Linux (Kali)

## Create User
sudo adduser testuser

## Set Password
sudo passwd testuser

## Add User to sudo Group (Administrator Privilege)
sudo usermod -aG sudo testuser

## Verify User Exists
cat /etc/passwd

## Delete User
sudo deluser testuser

---

## Observation
- A user account named **testuser** was successfully created.
- Administrator privileges were assigned using the **Administrators group (Windows)** and **sudo group (Linux)**.
- The user account was verified and then removed from the system.

## Conclusion
User management operations such as creating accounts, assigning privileges, verifying accounts, and deleting users are essential administrative tasks in both Windows and Linux operating systems.
